knowledge_graph.title: Apricot
knowledge_graph.description: An apricot is a fruit, or the tree that bears the fruit, of several species in the genus Prunus. Usually an apricot is from the species P. armeniaca, but the fruits of the other species in Prunus sect. Armeniaca are also called apricots.

related_questions.question: What do apricots do for your body?
related_questions.snippet: Apricots are also a good source of flavonoids, an antioxidant that helps to protect against inflammation and inflammatory illnesses, along with reducing your risk for obesity, diabetes, and heart disease. The main flavonoids in apricots are catechin, quercetin, and chlorogenic acids.
related_questions.title: Apricots: Health Benefits, Nutrition, and Uses - WebMD

related_questions.question: Is an apricot a peach?
related_questions.snippet: Apricots and peaches are stone fruits that bear similar coloring and shapes but differ in size and flavor. Peaches are sweeter and juicier, whereas apricots have a slightly tart flavor. Whichever you choose, both are excellent sources of many nutrients and can be incorporated into many dishes, desserts, and jams.
related_questions.title: Apricot vs. Peach: What's the Difference? - Healthline

related_questions.question: Are apricots the healthiest fruit?
related_questions.snippet: Not only are apricots healthy, but some experts also consider them a superfood. They're low in calories, high in fiber and, according to the U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA), contain these important nutrients: Beta-carotene. Lutein.
related_questions.title: 8 Health Benefits of Apricots

related_questions.question: What does apricot taste like?
related_questions.snippet: Flavor Profile Apricots are sweet with a distinct tarty taste and are not overly juicy. They taste almost like a cross between a peach and a plum.
